defaulte passenger safety.
default&#xa0;defaultQ2. defaultWhat lessons have been learned since the severe weather experienced in the winter of 2009-10? defaultWhat practical changes have been made to ensure the UK is now better equipped to deal with severe weather? default&#xa0;default2.1default&#xa0; 
defaultOn 12 March 2009 the then 
defaultSecretary of State (S
defaulto
defaultS) for Transport, 
defaultGeoff Hoon
default, made a statement to Parliament on the severe weather
default. The statement highlighted problems caused by the heavy snowfall and announced that the UK Roads Liaison Group (UKRLG) would review lessons that can b
defaulte learnt from the events of early February.  The UKRLG recommended what steps could be adopted by LHAs, trunk road authorities, producers of salt and other stakeholders to ensure the effective treatment of England’s road networks in order to ensure the nat
defaultion is better prepared should similar events occur in future years. 
default&#xa0;
default2.2default&#xa0; 
defaultUKRLG 
defaultreview 
default‘Lessons from the severe weather February 2009’
default 
defaultwas 
defaultpublished 
defaulton 
default4
default 
defaultAugust 2009
default and included 
defaulta package of 19 recommendations to develop and improve the highway maintenance f
defaultor future winters.
default  
default&#xa0;
default2.3default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Government responded to the review in a written Ministerial statement
default and the Code of Practice for the highways sector,
default Well-maintained Highways
default,
default was updated 
defaultin tandem with the announcement.
default&#xa0;
default2.4default&#xa0; 
defaultThe winter of 2009/10 
defaultwas the coldest in the UK for 30 years and the duration of freezing temperatures and the extent of coverage of both snow and ice were highly unusual. 
default&#xa0;
default2.5default&#xa0; 
defaultWith the experience of the second severe winter and with some concern as to whether all the lessons lear
defaultned from the previous winter had been acted upon, the then S
defaulto
defaultS for Transport commissioned a further but independent review in March 2010.  A three-man Panel led by David Quarmby, Chair of the 
defaultRAC
default Foundation was formed, 
defaultits purpose to 
defaultconsider and recommend
default practical measures to improve the response of England’s transport systems to severe winter weather. 
default&#xa0;
default2.6default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Quarmby review
default ‘The Resilience of England’s Transport System in Winter’
default published in October 2010, 
defaultendorsed all the recommendations of the UKRLG rev
defaultiew and noted that progress had been made by the roads sector.  
defaultA significant concern
default was that the supply
default of salt for highways was 
defaulta major issue.  The recommendation in the Interim Report was for a strategic reserve of a quarter of a million tonnes for 201
default0/11 (this was accepted by Government). 
default&#xa0;
default2.7default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Review recommended a combination of higher stockholding levels for the beginning of the winter season (with a new resilience bench-mark of 12 days/14 runs pre-season), permanent adoption of lower salt spread ra
defaulttes and a willingness by the two main suppliers to commit to higher
default throughput rates when the market
default demands.  
defaultIf successful these measures would secure sufficient resilience to meet the needs of a severe winter.  
default&#xa0;
default2.8default&#xa0; 
defaultThe
default RAC Foundation report, ‘Ploughing On
default – A review of hig
defaulthway resilience in Winter 2013’, covering both England and Wales 
defaultconcluded that good progress has been made by local highway authorities in winter service operations. 
default&#xa0;
default2.9default&#xa0; 
defaultThe report found that, without exception, local authorities are maint
defaultaining their level of spending on winter resilience despite general budget cuts. The review found evidence of cooperation between adjacent and intertwined county, district and parish councils; and that this activity was underpinned by improved consultation
default with local communities and better communications with the media and the public.
default&#xa0;
default2.10default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe report highlights where progress has been made and stated that ‘the valuable initiative and work of the National Winter Service Research Group (NWSRG) should be brought under the wing of the UKRLG’.  Many local highway authorities 
defaulthave reviewed salt sp
defaultread rates. F
defaultollowing the issue of the revised guidance from the UKRLG, 
defaultthere have been 
defaultsavi
defaultngs in the volumes of salt used. LHA’s are now
default applying salt at rates that are appropriate to varying circumstances. In practice, some of the salt saved has been re
defaultdirected into salt bins or salt bags, to support community efforts.
default&#xa0;
default2.11default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOn 18 September 2013
default an updated Appendix H
default 
defaultto Well-maintained Highways 
defaultwas published.  This latest revision of Appendix H has been carried out under the direction of the NWSRG on behalf 
defaultof the UKRLG and UK
default 
defaultR
defaultoads 
defaultB
defaultoard
default using information from the NWSRG Practical Guide for Winter Service (Practical Guide) and NWSRG member organisations, as well as other recent winter service research and information.  The spread rate tables in this guidance should help assist Local Highwa
defaulty Authorities to adopt the most suitable, and efficient in usage terms, salt spreading levels.  
default&#xa0;
default2.12default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs noted at the start of Appendix H:  “The guidance and recommendations contained within Appendix H relate to national Best Practice and it is recognised that
default local circumstances, including financial and other resource constraints, as well as political influences etc. can vary widely across the country. Authorities and operators will need to take all of these factors fully into account, when devising and revisi
defaultng their Winter Service policies and plans. Some of the recommendations and practices will, if adopted, also take a number of years to implement. For example, it is recognised that, in certain cases it could potentially take up to around 10 years or so for
default a major programme of change to be fully implemented.”
default&#xa0;
