default2.15default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRail –default Resilience plans should continue to include contingencies for disruption to services, including the provision of rail replacement bus services where appropriate.  Network rail and train operating companies generally have these plans in place, but they wil
defaultl need to continue to work with local highway/transport authorities to ensure that plans remain robust.
default&#xa0;
default2.16default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAviationdefault 
default- defaultThe UK’s aviation industry has made improvements to its ability to deal with severe winter weather. 
defaultSince 2009-10 Heathrow has invested £50 
defaultmillion in snow and ice clearance equipment and increased staff numbers available for snow clearance and Gatwick has invested a further £8million.  The Civil Aviation Act 2012 gave the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) powers for a new licensing regime, inclu
defaultding measures to ensure an airports operational resilience as a license condition (to come into force in 2014). The CAA has formalised its compliance monitoring team which is deployed at airport when there is major disruption to operations, monitoring and 
defaultensuring compliance with legislation on assisting passengers when flights are delayed or cancelled, with the powers to employ enforcement orders and penalties.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ3. defaultHow well prepared are the Government, local authorities and transport providers for adversedefault winter weather? What more should be done to ensure a coordinated response?default&#xa0;
default3.1default&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultoverall 
defaultmessage is that generally all sectors are better prepared than they were in the past but 
defaultthat all those involved in the delivery of a winter service
default shoul
defaultd not be comp
defaultlacent
default.
default&#xa0;
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.2default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultRAC Foundation Report
default,
default 
defaultPloughing
default On
default,
default identifies some areas of concern and ma
defaultkes an important point that 
defaultthe travelling public should take more responsibility in terms their preparations particularly in making journeys in bad weather.
default  There 
defaultmay be a need 
defaultto place more responsibility on road users to ensure they are prepared for severe winter conditions. Many of our European neighbours have legisla
defaultted to ensure this is the case.  Public expectations can be un
defaultrealistic and the role of the media
default and now social media needs careful consideration. 
default&#xa0;
default3.3default&#xa0; 
defaultFurther research and improvements to guidance in the use of alternative treatment methods
default is required
default.
default Both Europe and North America 
defaultmake use of a suite of treatment methods and do not rely predominantly
default on the application of salt. While the UK climate tends to be mild in nature there is still much to be learnt from abroad.
default  The National Winter Service Research Group (NWSRG) might benefit from this.
default&#xa0;
default3.4default&#xa0; 
defaultAs mentioned in
default point 
default1
default.2 above, CIHT has 
defaultconcerns about 
defaultreduced revenue funding
default to the sector (particularly Local Highway Authorities). This 
defaultmay 
defaultha
defaultve
default two effects:  firstly on day-to-day operations during a period of severe winter weather (and having sufficient  
defaultresources
default to address the situation)
default; secondly, a lack of funding 
defaultimpedes
default the ability to take on board some of the more significant changes required through capital investment.
default&#xa0;
default3.5default&#xa0; 
defaultCIHT would recommend that sufficient funding 
defaultcertainty 
defaultis provided to the transport sector to be able to ‘invest t
defaulto save’ to better manage winter resilience.  For instance new spreaders can optimise sal
defaultt usage (and thereby save cost), this would help authorities deliver on more significant change and improvements in the delivery of their winter service operations.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.6default&#xa0; 
defaultThe recognition that Highways incorporate footways and cycle
default 
defaultways is particularly relevant during periods of adverse weather and the recommendations of the Quarmby review are important in this regard. The needs of non-vehicular users and the clarity of adv
defaultice to householders to support the actions of local highway authorities in keeping footways clear is a continuing area for consideration. The role of funding from across government to reduce the amount of injury from slips and falls is a key area for furth
defaulter 
defaultdevelopment
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.7default&#xa0; 
defaultIt is essential that local highway authorities and bus operators work together to agree those    routes that will routinely be treated, and to clearly identify the routes or parts of routes where bus services may not operate in adverse con
defaultditions, with appropriate information being provided to customers.  This is particularly important in those areas, mainly the English metropolitan areas, where local highways and public transport are the responsibility of different authorities.
default&#xa0;
default3.8default&#xa0; 
defaultBus statio
defaultns are usually located away from 
defaultmajor 
defaultpublic highways, and therefore not necessarily on local authorities’ winter salting/gritting or snow clearance routes.  Most bus stations are owned and operated by the relevant local transport authority, and where thi
defaults is the same as the local highway authority it would be expected that winter treatment of bus stations would be part of the overall treatment strategy.  However, this may not always be the case in areas where local highways and public transport are the re
defaultsponsibility of different authorities, and in these areas it is crucial that the authorities work together on a strategy to ensure that bus stations and the relevant bus routes are properly treated in adverse winter conditions.  Some metropolitan transport
default authorities keep their own supply of road salt and salting vehicles for use in bus stations, but this 
defaultseems an unnecessary duplication of effort when the relevant highway authorities have their own equipment and materials, and could add bus stations to th
defaulteir winter treatment routes.
default&#xa0;
default3.9default&#xa0; 
defaultIn adverse winter conditions, it is often the case that local highway authorities will prioritise the treatment of roads, but give less attention, if any, to footways.  For car drivers and passengers this may cover all or almo
defaultst all of their journey, but for bus passengers clearly it will not.  All bus passengers will need to walk a certain distance at the start and finish of their bus journey, and they will be vulnerable to falls and injury if the footways aren’t appropriately
default treated.  Indeed, many passengers may not make the journey at all, if they have doubts about being able to negotiate footways at either or both ends of their bus journey.  In this respect, older and less able-bodied people are particularly vulnerable.  Th
defaultis should be picked up by local highway/transport authorities and bus operators in developing and implementing their winter resilience strategies.
default&#xa0;
default3.10default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAt times of major disruption to transport operations associated with adverse winter conditions, the dissemin
defaultation of information to passengers is crucial, to allow them to decide on the options available to them for their journey, or in some cases not to travel at all.  Within their winter resilience strategy, local transport authorities must have systems and pr
defaultocedures in place to provide information to passengers, and they must of course be flexible enough to allow for ever-changing conditions. 
default&#xa0;
default3.11default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultRail – defaultPerhaps the main concerns are around electrified railways, where power supply issues can become critical in 
defaultheavy snow.  There are generally few problems with 25kV AC overhead power supply systems, but 750V DC third-rail systems, such as exist in SE England and Merseyside, can be seriously affected in heavy snow falls, causing substantial disruption to services.
default  The longer-term solution is for third-rail systems to be converted to overhead power supply, but this would be expensive, and probably difficult to justify whilst the frequency of serious winter events remains low.  However, the rail industry will need t
defaulto continue to work on ensuring that third-rail systems are as resilient as possible.
default&#xa0;
default3.12default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNetwork Rail and train operating companies are usually very good at providing information for their customers when services are disrupted, but as previously identified, t
defaulthis flow of information must be part of an integrated information strategy, covering all transport modes.  In most situations where rail services are disrupted, e.g. for rail engineering works, train operators will provide rail replacement bus services.  T
defaulthis would probably not be possible where the disruption is caused by heavy snow, potentially leaving passengers stranded with no alternative transport.
default&#xa0;
default3.13default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs for bus services, it is important that rail stations and their environs, and at least the main pedes
defaulttrian routes to/from stations, are kept clear of snow and ice.  The 2009/10 winter weather showed that many passengers were reluctant to travel on snow-cleared rail routes where their walking routes at either end of the rail journey were hazardous.  It is 
defaultcrucial that all relevant agencies work together in developing and implementing robust resilience plans that consider the whole-journey implications for the population.
default&#xa0;
defaultConcluding remarksdefaultThe recognition of winter maintenance as a fundamental part of 
defaultcustomer services across transport networks has improved since the difficulties after 2009. We believe our comments will lead to the highways and transportation sector continuing to deliver improvements in dealing with an uncertain future scenarios
default.
